---
import { withBase } from "../utils/url";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <link rel="icon" href="data:image/svg+xml,<svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 100 100'><text y='.9em' font-size='90'>👹</text></svg>" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width" />
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/normalize.css">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://unpkg.com/magick.css">
    <meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
    <title>Nadeshiko Grind</title>
    <meta name="description" content="TUI tool to grind Japanese sentences using Nadeshiko" />
    <link rel="canonical" href="https://xifax.gitlab.io/nade_grind/" />

    <!-- Open Graph -->
    <meta property="og:title" content="NadeGrind // Japanese learning tool" />
    <meta property="og:description" content="TUI tool to grind Japanese sentences using Nadeshiko" />
    <meta property="og:image" content="/poster.webp" />
    <meta property="og:url" content="https://xifax.gitlab.io/nade_grind/" />
    <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
  </head>

  <body>
    <main>
      <header>
        <h1>Nadeshiko Grind</h1>
      </header>

      <section>
        Tool to grind/shadow Japanese words & sentences using
        <a href="https://nadeshiko.co">Nadeshiko</a>
        anime examples.
      </section>

      <section>
            <div class="screenshot-frame">
              <a href="#download">
                <video
                  autoplay
                  loop
                  muted
                  playsinline
                  poster={withBase("poster.webp")}
                  class="screenshot-video"
                >
                  <source src={withBase("demo.webm")} type="video/webm" />
                  <source src={withBase("demo.mp4")} type="video/mp4" />
                </video>
              </a>
            </div>
          </div>

      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Situation</h3>
        <p>Imagine, you have tricky 🗾 words from different apps, that don't stick well in your memory.
        You save them to Anki, print them on stickers, draw them on your bathroom walls, etc. Yet it helps little.</p>
        <p>Once, a wise balding Esperanto man from YouTube told me, that sometimes you need to just grind the sentences:
        repeat the words multiple times in different context, even if it's hard. </p>
        <p>This nerdy TUI app allows you to do it. </p>
        <p>It loads words from plain text and fetches (somewhat) relevant examples from 💮, with audio and sentence decomposition,
        separately from static SRS cards. <em>Again and again.</em> That is all.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h3>Usage</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Install from repo or download binary</li>
          <li>Get your words in a plain text file: export from Anki/Lute/LanguageReactor/etc, or save them into text file while you read/watch something</li>
          <li>Get API key from Nadeshiko <a href="https://nadeshiko.co/user/developer">dev page</a> (requires free registration)</li>
          <li>Launch app with the text file as an argument (defaults to words.txt) and paste the API key</li>
          <li>You may also drag and drop your text file onto the app executable (in Windows)</li>
          <li>Go through words randomly or in original order</li>
          <li>Fetch multiple examples for each word (if there are any)</li>
          <li>If you encounter an unkown word in a sentence, you may click on it to get a new example</li>
          <li>Persist in your grind and remove the words you are fed up with from the list</li>
          <li>Speak like a person from anime and fear nothing 👺</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section id="download">
        <h3>Binaries</h3>
        <button id="win"><a href="https://gitlab.com/api/v4/projects/xifax%2Fnade_grind/packages/generic/nade_grind/0.2.0/nade.exe">Windows EXE</a></button>
        <button id="linux"><a href="https://gitlab.com/api/v4/projects/xifax%2Fnade_grind/packages/generic/nade_grind/0.2.0/nade.bin">Linux BIN</a></button>
        <button id="source"><a href="https://gitlab.com/xifax/nade_grind">Source code</a></button>
        <button id="words"><a href="https://gitlab.com/xifax/nade_grind/-/raw/master/data/words.txt">Example words</a></button>
      </section>


      <section>
        <h3>Disclaimer</h3>
        <p>This app is not affiliated with Nadeshiko, nor with any of the creators of the service. It is just a <em>fun</em> experiment,
        made as a procrastination exercise in futility, instead of studying Anki cards and reading detective novels.</p>
        <p>You may encounter some 🐞 </p>
      </section>

      <footer>
        <p>Written by <a href="https://gitlab.com/demi.log">xifax</a> and is available under
        <a href="https://gitlab.com/xifax/nade_grind/-/raw/master/LICENSE">MIT license</a></p>
      </footer>

    </main>
  </body>
</html>

<style>

:root {
  --color-border: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.1);
  --border-subtle: var(--color-border);
  --radius-lg: 6px;
}

.screenshot-frame {
  /* faster for mouse tracking */
  transition: transform 0.2s ease-out;
  transform: perspective(1000px) rotateX(var(--rx)) rotateY(var(--ry)) scale(1);
}

.screenshot-frame:hover {
}

.screenshot-video {
  width: 90%;
  height: auto;
  display: block;
}

.screenshot-image {
  width: 90%;
  border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
}

#download a {
  text-decoration: none;
}

#download button {
  transition: all 0.25s ease;
}

/* Different hover colors per button */
button:hover { background-color: #4CAF50;}
#win:hover { background-color: #0078d4; }
#linux:hover { background-color: #f39c12; }
#source:hover { background-color: #6e40c9; }


</style>

<script>
// Follow the mouse!
const frame = document.querySelector('.screenshot-frame');

frame.addEventListener('mousemove', (e) => {
  const rect = frame.getBoundingClientRect();
  const x = e.clientX - rect.left;
  const y = e.clientY - rect.top;

  // sensitivity
  const rx = (y / rect.height - 0.5) * -20;
  const ry = (x / rect.width - 0.5) * 25;

  frame.style.setProperty('--rx', `${rx}deg`);
  frame.style.setProperty('--ry', `${ry}deg`);
});

// Reset to initial position
frame.addEventListener('mouseleave', () => {
  frame.style.setProperty('--rx', '0deg');
  frame.style.setProperty('--ry', '-0deg');
});
</script>
